{"type":"message","id":"41e536ec","parentId":"5fc3d8b9","timestamp":"2026-04-16T01:42:21.285Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Even the \"plain compress\" test (without XOR) is failing! This means `zlib.compress()` itself is producing data that can't be decompressed. But that should be impossible since zlib.compress always produces valid zlib data.\n\nWait, let me check if the issue is that zlib.compress produces a different format than zlib.decompress expects. In Python, `zlib.compress` produces raw deflate data (no zlib header), while `zlib.decompress` by default expects zlib-wrapped data (with header).\n\nActually no - in Python:\n- `zlib.compress()` produces zlib-wrapped data (with zlib header `0x78 0x9c` or similar)\n\n\n- `zlib.decompress()` expects zlib-wrapped data by default\n\nSo that's not the issue either. Let me look at the actual error more carefully - \"incorrect header check\" means the first few bytes are wrong, which suggests the data might be truncated or corrupted before decompression even starts.\n\nActually, I think I see it now. When I call `zlib.decompress()` on the base64-decoded data, the issue is that `bytes(dec)` creates a bytes object from the bytearray, but then `zlib.decompress()` expects the exact format that `zlib.compress()` produced. Let me trace through what's actually happening with the compressed output. I'm wondering if there's a `wbits` parameter mismatch between compress and decompressвЂ”`zlib.compress` uses `wbits=15` by default, but I should verify that `zlib.decompress` is expecting the same format. Let me also check the actual compressed data to see what format it's using, and then I'll run the round-trip test on a specific file to compare against what worked in the original pack.","thinkingSignature":"12c0c074b903d7ce9267bed1ca7756d4c09f4289c67a1fb3fc17c0c99398b19a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lvkw2yz2riul_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /root/.openclaw/work