{"type":"message","id":"28c4f24c","parentId":"4d0131f7","timestamp":"2026-04-16T01:48:32.047Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the comment changed but the actual code is the same (`path.join(destDir, \"skills\", entry.file)`). The comment is updated to explain the behavior correctly. The issue is that for ecosystem files, the path will be:\n`~/.openclaw/skills/agile-product-owner/skills/agile-product-owner/SKILL.md`\n\nBut actually this is CORRECT for the ecosystem! Because:\n- Ecosystem path: `ECOSYSTEM/skills/agile-product-owner/skills/agile-product-owner/SKILL.md`\n- After strip agent prefix: `skills/agile-product-owner/SKILL.md`\n- After prepend \"skills/\": `skills/skills/agile-product-owner/SKILL.md`Wait no! The code is `path.join(destDir, \"skills\", entry.file)` where `entry.file` is the FULL path like `agile-product-owner/skills/agile-product-owner/SKILL.md`. So `path.join(\"~/.openclaw\", \"skills\", \"agile-product-owner/skills/...\")` gives `~/.openclaw/skills/agile-product-owner/skills/...` which is a DOUBLE \"skills\" in the path. That doesn't match the original ecosystem path structure at all.\n\nThe real issue is that I need to handle two different path patterns: agent-defs entries like `senior-backend/SOUL.md` should become `~/.openclaw/skills/senior-backend/SOUL.md`, while ecosystem entries like `senior-backend/skills/senior-backend/SKILL.md` should become `~/.openclaw/skills/senior-backend/skills/senior-backend/SKILL.md`. The current approach of always prepending \"skills\" to the full entry file path doesn't work for both cases. I'm working through the exact path transformations for each case. For agent-defs files, I need to strip the agent prefix and nest under `skills/{agent}/`, while ecosystem files need a different handling since they already contain the `skills/` directory in their structure. Let me reconsider the actual directory layouts to get this right. The issue is that both patterns produce