{"type":"message","id":"6b420708","parentId":"f43e80f5","timestamp":"2026-04-16T01:56:39.080Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good - the install.sh checks if `$AHVHOLDING_API_KEY` is set, and if it is, it uses it. Since bash variables are inherited by child processes (the node script), `process.env.AHVHOLDING_API_KEY` in the node script will have access to it.\n\nBut wait - the user ran the piped command but the `AHVHOLDING_API_KEY` wasn't set in their environment, so the install.sh correctly detected it and exited. But then it still ran the setup with `--yes` and tried to prompt for credentials... No wait, looking at the output again:\n\n```\n в–¶ Chay setup cho team: dev...\n\n\n```\n\nThe script detected piped mode and auto-skipped the prompts, which triggered the credentials question that immediately exited because stdin wasn't available. So the root cause is that `AHVHOLDING_API_KEY` wasn't set in the environment before running the piped command, and now the install.sh needs to handle this case more gracefully by either requiring the key upfront or skipping the credentials prompt entirely.\n\nThe fix is to make the piped mode more robust by checking for the API key and either exiting with clear instructions or reading from the environment variable. But looking at the actual error message, the real problem is that the credentials prompt is appearing even though the script claims to be auto-skipping prompts, which means the credentials check isn't being bypassed properly in piped mode.\n\n```\n? AHV API Key (tu https://auto.ahvchat.com в†’ Account в†’ API Keys):\n```\n\nThe issue is that `collectCredentials()` runs regardless of the `--yes` flag, so when there's no stdin available in the pipe, the prompt hangs indefinitely. My fix addresses this by switching to `buildAnswersFromEnv()` when `--yes` is set, and the install script needs to properly export `AHVHOLDING_API_KEY` before calling the setup function.\n\nLooking at how bash handles variable exports, when install.sh runs and exports a variable, it should be available to the node script that gets spawned as a child process. The sequence is: install.sh checks if the variable is set, exports it if needed, then runs node with the --yes flag and team parameter. At that point, the exported variable should be accessible to the node script through `process.env`.\n\nThe core issue is that the previous attempt tried to read credentials interactively even with `--yes` set, which fails in non-interactive mode. My fix changes this so that when `--yes` is enabled, it pulls credentials from environment variables instead of prompting, and fails with a clear error message if the required `AHVHOLDING_API_KEY` isn't available.","thinkingSignature":"4112bc2399f1a529cd0280584740c15c5d05ca0faf4b2065a58b51fe2564f46c"},{"type":"text","text":"BГўy giб»ќ test thб»­ fix:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ubc00s7nnm2d_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/ahv-openclaw-setup && AHVHOLDING_API_KEY=\"sk-test123456789\" node bin/ahv-setup.js --yes 2>&1 | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":328,"output":623,"cacheRead":67057,"cacheWrite":483,"totalTokens":68491,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776304584411,"responseId":"062f74c9a8e07c2647d23ad2a84176fd"}}
