{"type":"message","id":"ed455b99","parentId":"5b08338d","timestamp":"2026-04-16T03:16:35.238Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The clone's git HEAD is at e051831 (which is correct), but the working tree file `bin/ahv-setup.js` still has the OLD code! This means the file was NOT updated by the pull. The working tree is dirty and the pull failed to update it (maybe there were uncommitted changes in the working tree).Wait - `git pull --quiet` should update the working tree even if there are local changes... unless the local changes conflict.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully - the install script ran `cd \"$INSTALL_DIR\" && git pull origin feat/full-setup-mcp --quiet`. If there were local changes in the repo (e.g., the old setup scripts from a previous run), the pull would fail with conflicts.But `git pull --quiet` would suppress error output... \n\nThe error I see is \"вќЊ Loi: object is not iterable\" which is from the setup script, not git. So the pull succeeded, but the working tree still shows the old code at line 185. I think the real issue is that the install script is cloning the repo fresh from GitHub, which creates the initial checkout, but then the `git pull` step that follows isn't properly updating the working tree files to match what's in the remote branch.\n\nWait, let me look at the git log again - the clone is on commit e051831, which matches the remote. But the actual file content at line 185 still has the old buggy code. That's strange because the fix I pushed was in commit a24ae7f, but the clone is still at e051831. The pull command should have fetched the latest commits and updated the working tree, but it seems like it didn't actually get to the a24ae7f commit yet. I'm realizing the git pull output might be truncatedвЂ”there's only one line showing \"Repo da co вЂ” pulling latest...\" but no confirmation of whether the pull actually completed or failed. Let me check the full output from the last test to see if there's an error I'm missing, and also verify whether a24ae7f is actually ahead of e051831 in the commit history. the local repo is already at e051831, so the pull doesn't fetch anything. But the working tree file shows the OLD code. The issue is likely that the working tree was dirty before the pull, and git pull failed silently because `--quiet` suppressed the error. I think the previous test run left uncommitted changes in `/root/.openclaw-setup/bin/ahv-setup.js`, so when the new test tried to pull from the remote branch, it encountered a conflict that was hidden by the quiet flag.","thinkingSignature":"7eb0bb2003b4d241866ea09ecfac698a418d622eede455636690b82ed0d82d19"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_jvp10usqgg64_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /root/.openclaw-setup && git status --short && echo \"---\" && git diff bin/ahv-setup.js | grep -A2 \"teamAgentIds\\|teamAgents\" | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":253,"output":605,"cacheRead":130531,"cacheWrite":433,"totalTokens":131822,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776309372075,"responseId":"062f877d42d55ae25dd8dd63ad67a946"}}
